 Information on MIT’s COVID-19 vaccination requirement can be found at the bottom of this posting. 
 
 AI POLICY FORUM (AIPF) COORDINATOR ,   Sloan School of Management , to assist with managing the logistics of and be actively involved in cultivating relationships with government officials and other AIPF partners. Will perform research in the context of technical, political, and economic issues that surround AI policy; guide intern and undergraduate student AI policy research projects; assist with preparing subject matter materials related to AIPF’s mission, including academic papers and conference reports; support AIPF leadership with planning and executing events and other activities, including setting agendas, scheduling, coordinating speakers, and preparing summary reports; promote AIPF by identifying sponsors/prospects' interests and concerns, cultivating relationships with prospective members, and facilitating commitments; advising AIPF leaders and faculty members on strategic plans to engage with prospects, maximize operational efficiency, enhance engagement, and resolve problems; and maintain thorough knowledge of faculty and student research and membership benefits to match sponsors/prospects with research. May assist in resolving issues concerning partners, intellectual property, technology licensing, and public relations. 
 
 Job Requirements 
 REQUIRED : bachelor’s degree (master’s preferred) in computer science or related field; at least two years’ experience working with policymakers, client relations, or professional development; one year of experience working in artificial intelligence and technology policy; strong oral and written (technical) communication skills, including effective business writing and presentation proficiency; ability to carry out collaborative policy research and effectively liaise with international policymakers and other partners; willingness to stay up-to-date on the current events, policy developments, and relevant technical matters; discretion with confidential information/issues; ability to work independently, prioritize, deliver high-quality results, and meet deadlines while managing multiple projects and competing demands; and strong organizational, time-management, problem-solving, and decision-making skills.  Job #20079-7 
Must be able to attend evening and/or weekend meetings and/or events up to 10% of the time. 
